05777nam a22008055i 9783111222318DE-B159720240306015011.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831112223187 a10.1515/97831112223182doi  a(DE-B1597)650442  a(OCoLC)1401577469  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE04a297.3/5569442223//eng/20231012eng1 aRubin (z"l), Uri, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBetween Jerusalem and Mecca :bSanctity and Redemption in the Qurʾān and the Islamic Tradition /cUri Rubin (z"l). 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (XI, 246 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aJudaism, Christianity, and Islam – Tension, Transmission, Transformation ,x2196-405X ;v2200tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPart One: Navel of the Earth -- t1 Muḥammad’s journey to the “Farthest Mosque” -- t2 Muḥammad’s ascension to heaven -- tPart Two: Land of Redemption -- t3 Israel’s redemption and “the Promise of the Latter Days” -- tPart Three: Land of Resurrection -- t4 Resurrection in al-Shām -- t5 Resurrection in Arabia -- tPart Four: Land of the Prophets -- t6 The Patriarchs in al-Shām -- t7 Ishmael and the progeny of Abraham -- t8 Abraham and Ishmael build the Kaʿba -- t9 The attempted sacrifice between al-Shām and Mecca -- t10 The Kaʿba and the Prophets -- tPart Five: Land of the Temple -- t11 Solomon’s Temple -- t12 “The first House established for the people” -- t13 The First House in Creation -- t14 The direction of prayer (qibla) within the sanctity space -- tPart Six: The Messianic Vision Inverted -- t15 Romans (al-Rūm), Jews and Muslims -- tSummary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book sheds new light on Jerusalem's status in early Islam. The sanctity of the city is already discerned in the Qurʾān. The vision of redemption that the Qurʾān displays coincides with the messianic expectations that have swept throughout the entire region, especially among the Jews, due to the attempted renewal of Jewish liturgy in Jerusalem following the Persian victory over Byzantium in 614.On the other hand, the Qurʾān also portrays the holiness of Mecca and the Kaʿba. This book shows how it promotes their pre-Islamic holiness around the image of Abraham and Ishmael. The changing balance between the sanctity of Jerusalem and the sanctity of Mecca, in favor of the latter, is noticeable in the Qurʾān as one proceeds from the Meccan sūras to the Medinan ones. The change occurs against the background of the twist in relations between Muḥammad and the Jews. This book also points out the correlation between Muḥammad's situation in Medina and events in Palestine involving the victory of the Byzantines over the Persians in 628, as alluded to in the opening passage of Sūrat al-Rūm (30).Thie work illuminates the growing sanctity of Jerusalem following the arrival of the first Muslims to Palestine. As in the Qurʾān, Mecca continued to struggle to preserve its status as a holy city vis-à-vis that of Jerusalem. Key aspects of this struggle are reflected in traditions in which patterns of sanctity move from Jerusalem to Mecca, and which this book also scrutinizes.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIslamxRelationsxJudaism. 0aJudaismxRelationsxIslam. 4aErlösung. 4aHeiligtum. 4aIslam. 4aJerusalem. 4aMekka.  aHadith.  aJerusalem.  aMecca.  aQur’an.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2023 Part 1z978311117578208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gr